Democracy without popular connection.
Something is characteristic of democracy in the sense that the government is elected by the people, and that is the case everywhere in the world.
Somehow, people have lost faith in elections.
Voter turnout is declining in many countries; in the case of European Parliament elections, the voter turnout was so ridiculously low that the legitimacy of the election result is questionable.
Apart from voter turnout, we have become accustomed to considering parties or candidates who receive 25% of the cast votes as "winners".
From Holland over Finland to Argentina and Japan, majority governments are formed on the basis of minorities.
Even apparent exceptions prove the opposite.
Only a few American presidents were elected by more than 10% of eligible voters. In fact, half of the eligible voters in the United States have not even registered to participate in the election; of those who have registered, half do not vote; of those who do vote, less than half vote for the winner.
Even Tony Blair's "earth-shattering" majority in the British House of Commons is on shaky ground: The Labour Party received only just over 40% of the votes in the last election in 2002, and this at a turnout of 60%.
Accordingly, only 24% of the total electorate supported Blair's party.
In most countries, the elections look very different compared to twenty, or even fifty years ago.
What has happened?
An answer might be that voters distrust the political parties.
The democratic election system functions in most countries due to the mediation of organizations that put forward candidates who enter for specific packages of political possibilities, for a "manifesto" or a "party platform."
For a number of reasons, this tried and tested practice no longer functions.
Ideological party programs have lost their power; Voters no longer accept the packages tied up by the parties, they want to reach out and pick something for themselves.
In addition, the political parties were transformed into machines composed of tightly organized cadres of insiders.
The paradox here is that the parties have become even more cliquey with the loss of their specific ideological orientation.
It's more important to belong to them than to share their specific convictions.
Such developments have alienated the parties from the voter.
Because most people do not want to belong to a particular party, only a minority is still playing the party game.
That increases public distrust of the political parties, not least because it is expensive to play along, just like in professional sports.
If the costs are borne by the taxpayer, it will be ill received.
However, without state financial support, parties would have to obtain money through channels that are often questionable, if not even illegal.
Many of the major political scandals of recent decades began with the financing of parties and their candidates.
Other indicators - such as the clear decline in membership - confirm that the parties have become unpopular.
Despite this, parties are indispensable for a democratic election.
The result is a clear separation between the visible political actors and the electorate.
Because parties are active in the parliaments, the effects of this separation concern one of the most important institutions of democracy.
People no longer believe that the parliaments represent them and thus are equipped with the necessary legitimacy to make decisions on their behalf.
At this point, a second, quite independent development comes into play.
People are more impatient today than ever before.
As consumers, they are accustomed to immediate satisfaction.
However, they have to wait as voters before they feel the results of the election, which they have cast at the ballot box.
Sometimes they never see the desired results.
Democracy needs time not only for elections, but also for discussions and careful weighing.
The consumer as voter won't accept this, however, and turns away as a result.
There are alternatives. However, each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
The "Direct Action" through demonstrations became a regular and often effective event.
For less mobile people, it could be replaced by the possibility of being able to express their opinion electronically; this ranges from internet chat forums to electronic messages to political leaders.
Then there are the non-governmental organizations. They often have undemocratic internal structures, but still seem to be more closely tied to the citizens.
In addition, there is, of course, the possibility of completely disconnecting and leaving politics to the experts, in order to focus on other areas of life.
This apparently harbors the greatest risks, as it fosters stealthy authoritarianism, a hallmark of our times.
But also other signs of the separation between politics and citizens cause an insecure condition, because no one can say anymore how representative the prevailing opinions are.
Some want to break the deadlock by more direct democracy.
However, establishing a lasting connection between leaders and followers cannot be achieved by simply reducing public discussion to simple voting options.
There is still much to be said for holding on to the classical institutions of parliamentary democracy and trying to link them more closely to the citizenry.
At least, unpopular parties and declining voter turnout might prove to be a temporary phenomenon.
New parties could emerge and elections and representative governments could gain more life.
However, this may probably not be enough to restore the general legitimacy which the elected governments have lost.
Therefore, the first concern of everyone who puts freedom in the constitution at heart must be to rethink democracy and its institutions.
